#### OPEC+

A significant number of non-OPEC member countries also participate in the organization's initiatives, such as voluntary supply cuts, to further align policy objectives between OPEC and non-OPEC members. [12] This broader group, known as OPEC+, includes Azerbaijan, Bahrain, Brunei, Brazil, Kazakhstan, Malaysia, Mexico, Oman, Russia, South Sudan, and Sudan. [194] [195]

The collaborative efforts among OPEC+ member countries led to the establishment of the Declaration of Cooperation (DoC) in 2017, which has since been extended multiple times due to its notable success. The DoC serves as a framework for cooperation and coordination between OPEC and non-OPEC nations. Additionally, OPEC+ members engage in further cooperative endeavors through the Charter of Cooperation (CoC), providing a platform for long-term collaboration. The CoC facilitates dialogue and the exchange of views on global oil and [energy market](/Energy_market) conditions, with the overarching objective of ensuring a secure energy supply and fostering lasting stability that benefits producers, consumers, investors, and the [global economy](/World_economy). [196]

#### Observers

Since the 1980s, representatives from countries such as Canada, Egypt, Mexico, Norway, Oman, and Russia have attended numerous OPEC meetings as observers. This arrangement facilitates an informal mechanism for coordinating policies. [197]

